SCAN 4: TWO-PARAMETER FIT (eps, N_scale)
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  Model: H0(N) = H0_local * (1 - eps)^(N/N_scale)
  Fit eps and N_scale to minimize chi^2 over 5 data points.
  Brute-force grid scan (no scipy).

  Grid scan: 99 x 99 = 9801 parameter combinations tested.

  Best eps (dimensionless)                 0.0001
  Best N_scale (dimensionless)             6.0
  Best chi^2 (dimensionless)               17.391618434
  chi^2 / dof (dof=3) (dimensionless)      5.7972061445

  Predictions at best fit:
            Data point    H0_meas    H0_pred      sigma       pull
  -------------------- ---------- ---------- ---------- ----------
       SH0ES local SNe      73.04     73.003        1.0   -0.03651
                  TRGB       69.8      73.01        1.7      1.888
       H0LiCOW lensing       73.3     72.797        1.8    -0.2795
               DES+BAO       67.4     71.833        1.2      3.694
            Planck CMB      67.36       67.2        0.5    -0.3205

  best_eps / (alpha/(3pi)) (dimensionless) 0.12915338649

SCAN 5: WHY 57 AND 39? INTEGER DECOMPOSITION
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  N for alpha^N = Lambda (dimensionless)   56.878233894
  N for (alpha/(3pi))^N = Lambda (dimensionless) 39.066296706

  INTEGER DECOMPOSITION:

  57 = 3 x 19
    3 = number of generations
    19 = numerator of b2_SM = -19/6
    19 = number of SM Weyl fermions per generation? No, that's 15.
    19 = dimension of the adjoint of... nothing standard.

  39 = 3 x 13
    3 = number of generations
    13 = number of particles in one SM generation
         (u_L, d_L, u_R, d_R, nu_L, e_L, e_R) x colors:
          3+3+3+3+1+1+1 = 15 Weyl fermions. Not 13.
    13 = from DM scan: (22/13)*pi ~ DM/baryon ratio

  SM PARTICLE COUNTING:
    Gauge bosons: 12 (8 gluons + W+ W- Z + photon)
    Higgs real dof: 4 (complex doublet)
    Weyl fermions: 45 (3 gen x 15)
    Total fields: 61
    Total dof: 12*2 + 4 + 45*2 = 118
    118/2 = 59 (close to 57, miss by 2)

  BOUNDARY TYPE COUNTING:
    Subatomic thresholds: 12 (6 quarks + 6 leptons)
    Gauge boson thresholds: 3 (W, Z, H)
    Composite thresholds: 2 (proton, neutron)
    Atomic/nuclear: 2
    Subtotal subatomic: 19
    Astronomical types: 8 (planet/star/ISM/gal/halo/cluster/fil/void)
    x 3 (enter/traverse/exit): 24
    Grand total: 43 (miss from 57 by 14)

  RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN 57 AND 39:
  57/39 (dimensionless)                    1.4615384615
    57/39 = 19/13 = 1.4615385
    This is the ratio of the two primes.

  CRITICAL CONNECTION:
    19 = |numerator of b2_SM| = 19 in b2 = -19/6
    13 = |numerator of b2_mod| = 13 in b2 + db2 = -13/6
    57/39 = 19/13 = b2_SM_num / b2_VL_num

    b2_SM = -3.1666666667, |numerator| = 19.0
    b2_mod = -2.1666666667, |numerator| = 13.0

  IMPLICATION:
    Lambda ~ alpha^(3 * 19) = alpha^(3 * |b2_SM_num|)
    Lambda ~ (alpha/(3pi))^(3 * 13) = (alpha/(3pi))^(3 * |b2_VL_num|)
    The cosmological constant scale is set by the SU(2) beta
    coefficient raised to the 3rd power (one per generation).

  NUMERICAL VERIFICATION:
    alpha^57 = 10^-121.79958 (target: 10^-121.53938, miss: -0.260194)
    (alpha/(3pi))^39 = 10^-121.33313 (target: 10^-121.53938, miss: 0.206256)

  log10(3*pi) (dimensionless)              0.97427112741

  Decomposition of (alpha/(3pi))^39:
    = alpha^39 * (1/(3pi))^39
    log10 = 39*-2.13683 + 39*-0.974271
           = -83.3366 + -37.9966 = -121.333

